Marc VanHeyningen (mvanheyn@whale.cs.indiana.edu) wrote:
: An interesting generalization ... is how to cryptographically
: create a situation whereby any m people in a group of n (of course,
: the problem is only hard when n > m > 1) must cooperate to read a
: message.

To achieve this, you choose a random polynom p of degree m-1 (or less;
the coefficients a1, ..., a(m-1) must be random, not excluding zero) with
the 0th coefficient, a0, equal to the secret key. Then you calculate
p(1), ..., p(n) and give each p(i) to person i (encrypted with i's
public key). Now any m people are able to interpolate the polynom
(e.g. using the formula of Lagrange) and so calculate p(0) = a0, the
secret key.

For practical purposes you can use polynoms over a finite field with
2^k elements (which exists for any k). It is only required that
2^k > n, because every person gets a different pair (i,p(i)).
If you choose a small k (maybe 8) but want to distribute a k*l bit
key, you can break the key into l pieces of k bits each and distribute
each single piece using the described procedure.

It can then be shown, if you know only m-1 different pairs (i,p(i)) then
all 2^k possible values for p(0) are equiprobable. Therefor the secret
key is perfectly secure against a coalition of m-1 persons.

For the arithmetic in finite fields you can read D.E. Knuth,
The art of computer programming, Vol 2.


Joerg

